{"title":"Broaden the Vision: Geo-Diverse Visual Commonsense Reasoning","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Existing visual commonsense reasoning benchmarks are largely Western-centric and do not evaluate models’ ability to use geo- and culture-specific commonsense, leading to unknown robustness on non-Western visual contexts.","method":"Introduce GD-VCR, a geo-diverse visual commonsense reasoning benchmark with 328 images and 886 QA pairs from Western, East Asian, South Asian, and African regions. The dataset is built via a three-stage pipeline: (1) collect images with explicit regional characteristics; (2) author high-order, object-referenced questions and answers in English using VCR-style question templates derived by clustering POS-tagged VCR questions with K-Means to minimize format mismatch; (3) construct 4-way multiple-choice by selecting distractors from the original VCR dev set’s correct answers using a relevance model (BERT-base) and a similarity model (stsb-roberta-base) to ensure high relevance (threshold ≥0.9) and low similarity (≤0.2) to the gold answer. Dataset stats (e.g., OOV rate 6.75% vs. VCR dev 12.70%) show comparable text/image properties while emphasizing regional commonsense."},{"problem":"How well do state-of-the-art V+L models trained on Western-centric data generalize to questions requiring geo-specific commonsense, and what drives any performance disparities?","method":"Fine-tune VisualBERT and ViLBERT on the original VCR training set and evaluate on GD-VCR across regions, plus conduct a human study with Western annotators. Findings: both models show large accuracy drops on non-Western regions (e.g., VisualBERT West 64.37% vs. East Asia 45.51%, −18.86 pp), while humans exhibit much smaller gaps. Analyze by scenario keywords and observe the largest gaps on culture-heavy scenarios (wedding, religion, festival). Further, annotate additional low-order QA pairs on the same images to disentangle perception vs. reasoning: models perform similarly across regions on low-order recognition (~60% with much smaller West vs. non-West gaps, e.g., −6.41 pp for East Asia) but degrade substantially on high-order reasoning in non-Western regions (e.g., Africa −26.25 pp), implicating missing geo-specific commonsense rather than basic visual recognition."}]}
